                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"indent(1)\">\n                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>\n            </p>\n            <p>Dear Sir!</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I thank you for a copy of your Bible. It<lb/> is indeed a handsome\n                edition. I am sorry that it came too<lb/> late to be noticed by me in the\n                Introduction<lb/> p. XV, which was printed before your Bible came to my<lb/> hands.\n                Still I shall notice it in its proper place.</p>\n            <p><persName>Dr. Huerst</persName> of <placeName>Leipzig</placeName> has (in his\n                Bibliotheca Judaica)<lb/> betrayed a profound ignorance of American literature.</p>\n            <p>So he wrote</p>\n            <p><persName>Isaac Leeser</persName> (Pr. in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>); The\n                Occident (Eine<lb/> Monatsschrift für jüd. Intressen). III. Jahrgänge.<lb/>\n                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>\n                <date>1843-46</date>.8.</p>\n            <p>He not only forgot to mention your own books, but<lb/> also those which you edited. I\n                called his attention to<lb/> this and other facts, and he desired me to give\n                him<lb/> correct statements in regard to <placeName>America</placeName>. Please<lb/>\n                send me a list of your own books and those<lb/> edited by you, together with the\n                necessary dates.</p>\n            <p>I believe my friend <persName>Kalisch</persName> is with you in\n                    <placeName>Ph.</placeName> I pray<lb/> you to encourage him; he is too much of\n                an <add>עניו</add> and<lb/> needs cheering up, if we are to expect something great\n                of<lb/> him.</p>\n            <p>I send you the first volume of my history by mail<lb/> because this is the cheapest\n                way. If you should think<lb/> it worth while to <sic>criticise</sic> it, I will call\n                your attention<lb/> to the passages in it which are new, and therefore<lb/> exposed\n                to criticism.</p>\n            <p>1. The distinction between history and religion. Introd. XV.</p>\n            <p>2. The death of <persName>Jacob</persName> p 35. 36.</p>\n            <p>3. The title of the Israelites to the land of <placeName>Canaan</placeName> p 37 to\n                40. 110.</p>\n            <p>4. Identity of the Anakims with Manetha's Hyksas<add>?</add>, who<lb/> were the\n                oppressors of <placeName>Israel</placeName> in <placeName>Egypt</placeName> p.\n                41-54</p>\n            <p>5. Exposition of the Decalogue p. 80-84</p>\n            <p>6. The <sic>defence</sic> of <persName>Joshua</persName>\n                <sic>p</sic> 213-216</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p34m91x1v/canvas/p1"
                }
